{
  "Elements in the periodic table are arranged by increasing:": "",
  "Number of neutrons": "",
  "Atomic number": "",
  "Atomic mass": "",
  "Density": "",
  "The modern periodic table arranges elements by atomic number (number of protons). Mendeleev originally arranged them by atomic mass, but Henry Moseley corrected this using atomic number.": "",
  "A horizontal row on the periodic table is called a:": "",
  "Block": "",
  "Period": "",
  "Group": "",
  "Family": "",
  "There are 7 periods in the modern periodic table. Each period corresponds to a principal energy level — all elements in Period 3, for example, have 3 electron shells.": "",
  "A vertical column on the periodic table is called a:": "",
  "Series follow": "",
  "Group (or family)": "",
  "Period as obs": "",
  "Row, particul": "",
  "Groups (columns) contain elements with similar chemical properties because they have the same number of valence electrons. There are 18 groups in the modern periodic table.": "",
  "Elements in the same group share similar:": "",
  "Colors": "",
  "Chemical properties": "",
  "Atomic masses": "",
  "Elements in the same group have the same number of valence electrons, giving them similar chemical behavior. For example, all alkali metals (Group 1) are highly reactive and form +1 ions.": "",
  "How many periods are in the modern periodic table?": "",
  "18": "",
  "8": "",
  "6": "",
  "7": "",
  "The periodic table has 7 periods. Period 1 has 2 elements (H, He), periods 2 and 3 have 8 each, periods 4 and 5 have 18 each, and periods 6 and 7 have 32 each.": "",
  "The staircase line on the periodic table separates:": "",
  "Large from small atoms": "",
  "Metals from nonmetals": "",
  "Gases from solids": "",
  "Natural from synthetic elements": "",
  "The zigzag or staircase line runs from boron (B) to astatine (At). Metals are to the left, nonmetals to the right, and metalloids (B, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Te) border the line.": "",
  "The periodic table was first organized by:": "",
  "John Dalton": "",
  "Albert Einstein": "",
  "Niels Bohr": "",
  "Dmitri Mendeleev": "",
  "In 1869, Mendeleev arranged elements by atomic mass and left gaps for undiscovered elements. His predictions proved remarkably accurate when gallium, germanium, and scandium were later discovered.": "",
  "Where are metals generally found on the periodic table?": "",
  "In the upper right corner": "",
  "Along the staircase line only": "",
  "To the left and center": "",
  "Only in period 1": "",
  "About 75% of elements are metals. They occupy the left and center of the table, including alkali metals (Group 1), alkaline earth metals (Group 2), and transition metals (Groups 3-12).": "",
  "Which property is characteristic of metals?": "",
  "Brittle as solids": "",
  "Poor conductors": "",
  "Good conductors of heat and electricity": "",
  "Dull appearance": "",
  "Metals are shiny (lustrous), malleable (can be hammered into sheets), ductile (can be drawn into wires), and good conductors. These properties result from metallic bonding and delocalized electrons.": "",
  "How many groups (columns) are in the modern periodic table?": "",
  "12": "",
  "The modern table has 18 groups numbered 1-18. Groups 1-2 and 13-18 are the main-group (representative) elements, while groups 3-12 are the transition metals.": "",
  "What is a metalloid?": "",
  "A nonmetal that looks like a metal when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "An artificial element, particularly regarding properties as typically": "",
  "A metal that has been melted following the established framework": "",
  "An element with properties of both metals and nonmetals, found along the staircase line": "",
  "Metalloids (B, Si, Ge, As, Sb, Te) have intermediate properties. Silicon, for example, is a semiconductor — it conducts electricity under certain conditions but not others, making it essential for electronics.": "",
  "What are transition metals?": "",
  "Elements in Groups 3-12 that form colorful compounds and have multiple oxidation states": "",
  "Elements in Period 1 only": "",
  "Elements that are transitioning from metal to nonmetal": "",
  "Radioactive elements at the bottom of the table": "",
  "Transition metals (Groups 3-12) include familiar metals like iron, copper, gold, and silver. They can form multiple ions (e.g., Fe²⁺ and Fe³⁺) because they have partially filled d orbitals.": "",
  "What are the alkali metals?": "",
  "The lanthanide series": "",
  "Group 18 elements that are alkaline": "",
  "Group 1 elements (Li, Na, K, etc.) — highly reactive metals with 1 valence electron": "",
  "Metals that dissolve in acid": "",
  "Alkali metals are the most reactive metals. They react vigorously with water (Na + H₂O → NaOH + H₂), become more reactive down the group, and are never found pure in nature.": "",
  "What are noble gases?": "",
  "Gases found only in a nobleman's laboratory": "",
  "Group 18 elements (He, Ne, Ar, etc.) — very stable and unreactive with full outer electron shells": "",
  "Gases that are heavier than air": "",
  "Radioactive gas elements": "",
  "Noble gases have complete valence shells (8 electrons, except He with 2), making them extremely stable. They rarely form compounds and are used in lighting (neon signs) and as inert atmospheres.": "",
  "What is a nonmetal?": "",
  "An element that cannot form compounds": "",
  "An element that is a poor conductor, often brittle as a solid, and located to the right of the staircase line": "",
  "Any element that is a gas at room temperature": "",
  "An element lighter than hydrogen": "",
  "Nonmetals include essential elements like carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and halogens. They tend to gain electrons in chemical reactions, can be gases, liquids (bromine), or solids, and have lower melting points than metals.": "",
  "What are halogens?": "",
  "Noble gas compounds, particularly regarding what based on established principles": "",
  "Elements that produce light according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Group 17 elements (F, Cl, Br, I, At) — highly reactive nonmetals with 7 valence electrons": "",
  "Group 1 metals, particularly regarding when under normal circumstances": "",
  "Halogens need only 1 electron to achieve a stable octet, making them very reactive. Fluorine is the most reactive nonmetal. They form salts when combined with metals (halogen means 'salt-former').": "",
  "What are the alkaline earth metals?": "",
  "Group 1 elements, particularly regarding earth following the": "",
  "Elements used to make bases according to conventional analysis": "",
  "Group 2 elements (Be, Mg, Ca, etc.) — reactive metals with 2 valence electrons": "",
  "Metals found in alkaline soil only in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "Alkaline earth metals are less reactive than alkali metals but still reactive. Calcium (Ca) is essential for bones, magnesium (Mg) for chlorophyll in plants. They form +2 ions by losing 2 electrons.": "",
  "What are the lanthanides and actinides?": "",
  "Noble gas compounds, particularly regarding actinides under normal circumstances": "",
  "Two series of elements placed below the main table, filling f orbitals (periods 6 and 7)": "",
  "The lightest elements on the table as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Synthetic elements only, particularly regarding metals when measured": "",
  "Lanthanides (elements 57-71) and actinides (elements 89-103) are 'inner transition metals' placed below to keep the table compact. All actinides are radioactive; many are synthetic.": "",
  "What does 'periodic' mean in the context of the periodic table?": "",
  "Elements exist for a limited period of time": "",
  "The table is updated periodically": "",
  "Properties repeat at regular intervals when elements are arranged by atomic number": "",
  "Properties change randomly": "",
  "The periodic law states that properties of elements are a periodic function of their atomic numbers. For example, the pattern of reactivity (high → low → high) repeats in each period.": "",
  "What is the s-block on the periodic table?": "",
  "Groups 1-2 plus helium, where the outermost electrons fill s orbitals": "",
  "The noble gases": "",
  "Elements that start with the letter S": "",
  "The transition metals section": "",
  "The periodic table is divided into blocks based on which orbital the last electron occupies: s-block (Groups 1-2), p-block (Groups 13-18), d-block (Groups 3-12), and f-block (lanthanides/actinides).": "",
  "A chemistry student finds that lithium (Li), sodium (Na), and potassium (K) all react vigorously with water. This is because they are all in:": "",
  "The same group (Group 1) and share similar chemical properties": "",
  "The noble gas group following conventional understanding": "",
  "The same period, particularly regarding reactions": "",
  "The metalloid region when measured under": "",
  "Li, Na, and K are all alkali metals (Group 1) with 1 valence electron. They easily lose this electron, causing vigorous reactions with water that produce hydrogen gas and heat.": "",
  "A scientist discovers that silicon is used in computer chips because it is a semiconductor. On the periodic table, silicon is classified as a:": "",
  "Metal — because it conducts electricity": "",
  "Nonmetal — because it is brittle": "",
  "Noble gas — because it is stable": "",
  "Metalloid — it has properties between metals and nonmetals": "",
  "Silicon is a metalloid along the staircase line. It conducts electricity partially (semiconductor), making it ideal for transistors and microchips — the foundation of modern electronics.": "",
  "Neon signs glow different colors using noble gases. Why don't these gases react with the glass or electrodes?": "",
  "They are too heavy to react": "",
  "The glass prevents reactions": "",
  "Noble gases have full outer electron shells, making them chemically inert": "",
  "They are kept at very low temperatures": "",
  "Noble gases (Group 18) have complete valence shells and extremely high ionization energies. When electrically excited, their electrons emit specific colors of light without forming chemical bonds.": "",
  "Mendeleev left gaps in his periodic table and predicted the properties of undiscovered elements. When gallium was discovered, it matched his prediction for 'eka-aluminum.' This demonstrates:": "",
  "That eka-aluminum and gallium are different elements": "",
  "That Mendeleev already knew about gallium": "",
  "The predictive power of the periodic table's organization": "",
  "That the periodic table is based on guesswork": "",
  "Mendeleev predicted the density, melting point, and oxide formula of 'eka-aluminum.' When Lecoq de Boisbaudran discovered gallium in 1875, its properties closely matched — validating the periodic law.": "",
  "A student notices that fluorine (F) and chlorine (Cl) both react strongly with metals to form salts. Using the periodic table, what explains this similarity?": "",
  "They are in the same period": "",
  "They have the same number of protons": "",
  "They are both metals": "",
  "They are in the same group (Group 17) and both have 7 valence electrons": "",
  "Fluorine and chlorine are halogens (Group 17) with 7 valence electrons. They both need just 1 more electron to fill their octet, so they readily react with metals. 'Halogen' means 'salt-former.'": "",
  "An engineer selects copper (Cu) for electrical wiring. Copper is located in the transition metals region. Which property makes it ideal for wiring?": "",
  "It is a nonmetal, particularly regarding freely when": "",
  "Excellent electrical conductivity and ductility (can be drawn into wires)": "",
  "It is very brittle, particularly regarding copper under": "",
  "Its low melting point, particularly regarding delocalized": "",
  "Copper is the second-best electrical conductor (after silver). As a transition metal, it has delocalized electrons that move freely, enabling excellent conductivity. Its ductility allows thin wire production.": "",
  "Carbon (C), nitrogen (N), and oxygen (O) are all in Period 2 of the periodic table. What do they have in common structurally?": "",
  "They all have 8 protons": "",
  "They are all metals": "",
  "They all have 2 electron shells": "",
  "They all have the same number of valence electrons": "",
  "All Period 2 elements have electrons in 2 energy levels (shells). However, they differ in their number of valence electrons: C has 4, N has 5, and O has 6, which is why they are in different groups.": "",
  "A researcher notices that cesium (bottom of Group 1) reacts explosively with water, while lithium (top of Group 1) reacts gently. This trend occurs because:": "",
  "Lithium is not actually a metal": "",
  "Cesium is always stored at higher temperatures": "",
  "Larger atoms lose their valence electron more easily due to greater distance from the nucleus": "",
  "Cesium has more valence electrons than lithium": "",
  "Going down Group 1, atoms get larger and the valence electron is farther from the nucleus with more shielding. This makes it easier to remove, increasing reactivity. Cesium reacts more violently than lithium.": "",
  "The element hydrogen (H) is placed in Group 1 but behaves differently from alkali metals. Some tables place it separately. Why is its placement controversial?": "",
  "It should be in Group 18, particularly regarding unique following the established framework": "",
  "H has 1 valence electron like Group 1 metals but is a nonmetal that can also gain 1 electron like halogens": "",
  "It has no electrons, particularly regarding tables as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Hydrogen is not a real element, particularly regarding alkali as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "Hydrogen has 1 valence electron (like alkali metals) but is a nonmetal gas. It can lose an electron (forming H⁺, like metals) or gain one (forming H⁻, like halogens), making it unique.": "",
  "A forensic scientist uses the periodic table to identify an unknown sample. The sample is a brittle, shiny solid that conducts electricity slightly. Based on these properties, the element is most likely a:": "",
  "Noble gas, particularly regarding elements": "",
  "Metalloid — it shows properties of both metals and nonmetals": "",
  "Alkali metal, particularly regarding solid when": "",
  "Halogen, particularly regarding solid under": "",
  "Metalloids are shiny like metals but brittle like nonmetals, and they are semiconductors (partial conductors). Elements like silicon and germanium fit this description and are found along the staircase line.": ""
